# Bulk Data Loading

This notebook introduces the Splice Machine Bulk HFile Import mechanism, which you can use to import data into your database in a highly performant manner. Bulk importing splits a data file into temporary HFiles (store files) before it is imported into your database by directly loading the generated StoreFiles into your Region Servers. In this notebook we will walk you through a simple example, after which you will be able to bulk import data into your database. This notebook contains these sections:

* The *Bulk Data Import Checklist* summarizes important details about the format of the data you're importing.
* The *Automatic Bulk Data Import* method shows you how to quickly bulk import your data
* The *Manual Bulk Data Import* allows you to control the splitting of data
* *Using the `BULK_IMPORT_HFILE` Command* shows the syntax for importing data using the `BULK_IMPORT_HFILE` system procedure

When you use bulk HFile import your data files are essentially split into temporary hadoop files (hfiles) that are directly loaded into the region servers. Ideally the process will create hfiles of equal size that will allow the data to be spread across all region servers equally. There are two methods for splitting the data into hfiles.

* Automatic Splitting - The system will sample the data in an attempt to determine the optimal split points. This is the quicker and easier method but does not always ensure you have the ideal splitting of the data
* Manual Splitting - This method improves the performance of the bulk data import process as it will not sample the data for the split points. Instead, you will need to provide the split points so the procedure knows where to split your data. This will require you to know the data well enough to provide the split points.

Lastly we will walk you through step-by-step examples of using both the automatic and manual process bulk data import processes.

%md ## Bulk Data Import Checklist When you bulk import data from flat files into your database, you need to specify a number of details about your data files to get them correctly imported. Before starting this process, please make sure your data formats will work, as defined here:
Data File Detail Specific Requirements
Field delimited? The fields in each row must have delimiters between them
Rows terminated? Each row must be terminated with a newline character
Header row included? Header rows are not allowed; if your data contains one, you must remove it.
Date, time, timestamp data types If you are using date, time, and/or timestamp data types in the target table, you need to know how that data is represented in the flat file; your file must use a consistent representation, and you must specify that format when using the import command.
Char and Varchar data

If any of your char or varchar data contains your delimiter character, you need to use a special character delimiter.

If any of your char or varchar data contains newline characters, you need to use the oneLineRecords parameter.

It is a good idea to test your import, delimiting, date formatting, etc., on a small amount of data first before loading all of your data. That's what we'll do in this notebook.

paragraphs.text:
%md
## Automatic Bulk Data Import

If you choose to use the automatic bulk data import process all you need to do is run the `BULK_IMPORT_HFILE` system procedure. Splice Machine will automatically generate the split points by sampling the data that is being imported. If you discover that the automatic bulk data import process is not as performant as expected you should consider the manual bulk data import process. Before you execute `BULK_IMPORT_HFILE` be sure to create the table first in Splice Machine as well as any known indexes that may be needed.

paragraphs.text:
%md
## Manual Bulk Data Import

If you choose to use the manual bulk data import process there are some additional steps you will need to perform before you can call the `BULK_HFILE_IMPORT` system procedure. You will need to pre-split the data by providing a csv file that contains all the split points for your data. Follow these steps to manually bulk import your data:

1. Create the table in your Splice Machine database
2. Optionally, create any index(es) on the table
3. Pre-split the table
4. Call the `SPLIT_TABLE_OR_INDEX` system procedure for the table
5. Optionally, pre-split any index(es) on the table
6. Optionally, call the `SPLIT_TABLE_OR_INDEX` system procedure for the index(es)
7. Call the `BULK_IMPORT_HFILE` system procedure

### 2. Optionally, create any index(es) on the table

If you’re going to index the table you’re importing, Splice Machine recommends that you create the index prior to using bulk import. This allows the index to also be pre-split into regions, which will prevent downstream bottlenecks.

paragraphs.text:
%md ### 3. Pre-split the table When you pre-split a table you are essentially identifying primary key values that can horizontally split the data into roughly equal parts. Here is a simple example. Let's say you have some order data that you want to load. The data contains a column for order id that has values from 1 to 999,999. We can pre-split this table into 4 roughly equal parts by using the order id column and specifying the values 250000, 500000, and 750000. Create a file that contains: ``` 250000 500000 750000 ```

Split key values can be multiple columns in which case each column value would be delimited by a pipe character (|). For example: 200000|2019-01-01

paragraphs.text:
%md ### 4. Call the SPLIT_TABLE_OR_INDEX system procedure for the table Syntax for the `SPLIT_TABLE_OR_INDEX` command looks like this: ``` call SYSCS_UTIL.SYSCS_SPLIT_TABLE_OR_INDEX ( schemaName, tableName, indexName, columnList | null, fileName, columnDelimiter | null, characterDelimiter | null, timestampFormat | null, dateFormat | null, timeFormat | null, maxBadRecords, badRecordDirectory | null, oneLineRecords | null, charset | null, ); ``` Notice that many of the parameters allow you to apply the default value by specifying `null`.

You can find full details about these parameters, including the default value for each, in our `SPLIT_TABLE_OR_INDEX` documentation.

You can find full details about these parameters, including the default value for each, in our `SPLIT_TABLE_OR_INDEX` documentation.

You can find full details about these parameters, including the default value for each, in our `BULK_IMPORT_HFILE` documentation.

You'll notice that after you run the paragraph, you see a short report that indicates how many rows were successfully loaded, and how many failed to load, In this example, all 15 million rows were successfully loaded. You have probably also noticed that we used default values by specifying `null` for all of the parameters that have defaults; here's what those defaults mean:
Parameter NULL Value Details
insertColumnList Our column list exactly matches the columns and ordering of columns in the table, so there's not need to specify a list.
columnDelimiter Our data uses the default comma character (,) to delimit columns.
stringDelimiter None of our data fields contain the comma character, so we don't need a string delimiter character.
timestampFormat Our data matches the default timestamp format, which is yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss
dateFormat Our data doesn't contain any date columns, so there's no need to specify a format.
timeFormat Our data doesn't contain any time columns, so there's no need to specify a format.

%md
## Step-by-Step Example of Manual Bulk Data Import

This example will walk you through the manual bulk data import process one step at a time. In these steps you will:

1. *Create a Database Schema and Table*
2. *Manually Split the Table*
2. *Run the Manual Bulk Import Data Procedure*
3. *Review Imported Data*

msg.data:
Step-by-Step Example of Manual Bulk Data Import

This example will walk you through the manual bulk data import process one step at a time. In these steps you will:

  1. Create a Database Schema and Table
  2. Manually Split the Table
  3. Run the Manual Bulk Import Data Procedure
  4. Review Imported Data

paragraphs.text: %md ### 1. Create a Database Schema and Table You can get started by clicking the *Run* button to run the next paragraph in this Notebook, which uses the `%splicemachine` interpreter to: * Create the `customer_bulk_import_example2` table in your database.

msg.data:
1. Create a Database Schema and Table

You can get started by clicking the Run button to run the next paragraph in this Notebook, which uses the %splicemachine interpreter to:

  • Create the customer_bulk_import_example2 table in your database.

paragraphs.text:
%splicemachine

 CREATE TABLE DEV3.CUSTOMER_BULK_IMPORT_EXAMPLE2 (
 C_CUSTKEY INTEGER NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
 C_NAME VARCHAR(25),
 C_ADDRESS VARCHAR(40),
 C_NATIONKEY INTEGER NOT NULL,
 C_PHONE VARCHAR(15),
 C_ACCTBAL DECIMAL(15,2),
 C_MKTSEGMENT VARCHAR(10),
 C_COMMENT VARCHAR(117)
 );

msg.data: Query executed successfully. Affected rows : 0

paragraphs.text:
%md ### 2. Manually Split the Table Now we will need to create the split keys for our data. The customer data file that we are loading contains a customer key column that has values from 1 to 15,000,000. For this exercise we will evenly split the data into 4 hfiles so the keys will look like this: 
3750000
7500000
11250000
For every N lines of split data you specify, you’ll end up with N+1 regions; for example, the above 3 splits will produce these 4 regions: 
0 -> 3750000
3750001 -> 7500000
7500001 -> 11250000
11250001 -> (last possible key value)
We have created this file for you. All you need to do is *Run* the next paragraph which calls the `SPLIT_TABLE_OR_INDEX` procedure. The file containing the split keys is one of the parameters passed to `SPLIT_TABLE_OR_INDEX`.

msg.data:

Now we will need to create the split keys for our data. The customer data file that we are loading contains a customer key column that has values from 1 to 15,000,000. For this exercise we will evenly split the data into 4 hfiles so the keys will look like this:

3750000
7500000
11250000

For every N lines of split data you specify, you’ll end up with N+1 regions; for example, the above 3 splits will produce these 4 regions:

0 -> 3750000
3750001 -> 7500000
7500001 -> 11250000
11250001 -> (last possible key value)

We have created this file for you. All you need to do is Run the next paragraph which calls the SPLIT_TABLE_OR_INDEX procedure. The file containing the split keys is one of the parameters passed to SPLIT_TABLE_OR_INDEX.

paragraphs.text:
%splicemachine

call SYSCS_UTIL.SYSCS_SPLIT_TABLE_OR_INDEX(
    'DEV3',
    'CUSTOMER_BULK_IMPORT_EXAMPLE2',
    null, 
    'C_CUSTKEY',
    '/opt/data/customer-split-keys.csv',
    '|', 
    null, 
    null, 
    null,
    null, 
    -1, 
    '/tmp', 
    true, 
    null
);

paragraphs.text: %md ### 3. Run the Manual Bulk Import Data Procedure Now we'll bulk import our data. As in the previous example we will be bulk importing the customer table data for TPCH-100. This time we have pre-split the table so we will not need to sample the data before importing. The main difference between this execution of `BULK_IMPORT_HFILE` is the last parameter which is `skipSampling`. Import the data in this file by clicking the *Run* button to run the next paragraph, which calls our `BULK_IMPORT_HFILE` command.

msg.data:
3. Run the Manual Bulk Import Data Procedure

Now we’ll bulk import our data. As in the previous example we will be bulk importing the customer table data for TPCH-100. This time we have pre-split the table so we will not need to sample the data before importing. The main difference between this execution of BULK_IMPORT_HFILE is the last parameter which is skipSampling.

Import the data in this file by clicking the Run button to run the next paragraph, which calls our BULK_IMPORT_HFILE command.

paragraphs.text:
%splicemachine

call SYSCS_UTIL.BULK_IMPORT_HFILE('DEV3', 'CUSTOMER_BULK_IMPORT_EXAMPLE2', null, 's3a://splice-benchmark-data/flat/TPCH/100/customer', '|', null, null, null, null, 0, '/tmp', true, null, '/tmp/TMP_HFILE', true);
